-== Training Procedure
-
-Standard backpropagation is used to learn the best parameters for scene fidelity, while loss can be measured using common image similarity metrics.
-
-[SSIM metrics]
-
-[Image Reconstruction L1 or L2 loss]
-
-Specific Loss for 4DGS + Loss variations (see USPLAT)
-
-*Specific Loss for 4DGS and Loss Variations.* 
-
-The standard 4DGS-Native training objective combines a photometric L1 reconstruction term with a structural similarity term:
-
-$
- cal(L)_"rgb" = (1 - lambda_"dssim") cal(L)_1 + lambda_"dssim" cal(L)_"SSIM"
-$
-
-An opacity mask loss penalizes Gaussians with high opacity in sky or background regions, identified via a binary mask sky = $1 - m_"gt"$ derived from the ground-truth alpha channel:
-
-$
- cal(L)_"opa" = -1 / abs(Omega) sum_(p in Omega) s k y(p) dot log(1 - o(p))
-$
-
-where $o(p) = alpha(p)$ is the rendered opacity at pixel $p$. This discourages the model from placing opaque Gaussians in regions that should be transparent.
-
-Two motion regularization terms further constrain the dynamic behaviour of the Gaussian set. A rigidity loss enforces velocity coherence among spatially proximate Gaussians, weighted by spatial distance:
-
-$
- cal(L)_"rigid" =
- 1 / (k dot G)
- sum_(i=1)^G
- sum_(j in cal(N)(i))
- exp(-100 dot d_(i j)) dot
- norm(dot(mu)_i - dot(mu)_j)_2
-$
-
-where $dot(mu)_i$ is the temporal velocity of Gaussian $i$ evaluated by finite difference of its mean position, $cal(N)(i)$ denotes its $k$ nearest spatial neighbours, and $d_(i j)$ is the squared Euclidean distance between Gaussians $i$ and $j$. A global motion loss additionally penalizes high-velocity Gaussians directly:
-
-$
- cal(L)_"motion" = 1 / G sum_(i=1)^G norm(dot(mu)_i)_2
-$
-
-These four terms constitute the baseline training objective of 4DGS-Native, active throughout the full training run.
-
-*Uncertainty-Aware Graph Losses.* 
-
-Following convergence of the base model at iteration $N_"start"$ — coinciding with the end of densification so that the Gaussian count is stable — we augment the objective with the uncertainty-aware graph losses of USplat4D. The total loss from iteration $N_"start"$ onward becomes:
-
-$
- cal(L) =
- cal(L)_"rgb"
- + lambda_"key" cal(L)_"key"
- + lambda_"non-key" cal(L)_"non-key"
-$
-
-The key node loss anchors reliable, well-observed Gaussians to their pretrained positions and enforces local geometric consistency among their graph neighbours:
-
-$
- cal(L)_"key" =
- sum_t sum_(i in V_k)
- norm(bold(p)_(i,t) - bold(p)_(i,t)^circle)_(U^(-1)_(w,t,i))^2
- + cal(L)_"motion,key"
-$
-
-where $bold(p)_(i,t)^circle$ denotes the pretrained position of Gaussian $i$ at frame $t$, and $U^(-1)_(w,t,i)$ is the inverse anisotropic uncertainty matrix:
-
-$
- U_(i,t) =
- R_"wc"
- op("diag")(r_x u_(i,t), r_y u_(i,t), r_z u_(i,t))
- R_"wc"^T
-$
-
-with $[r_x, r_y, r_z] = [1, 1, 0.01]$, down-weighting depth corrections by a factor of 100 to account for the inherent unreliability of monocular depth. The scalar uncertainty $u_(i,t)$ is derived from the alpha-blending weights accumulated during rendering:
-
-$
- sigma^2_(i,t) =
- 1 / sum_(h in P_(i,t)) (T^h_(i,t) dot alpha_i)^2,
- quad
- u_(i,t) = cases(
-   sigma^2_(i,t) & "if " bb(1)_(i,t) = 1,
-   phi & "otherwise",
- )
-$
-
-where $bb(1)_(i,t)$ is a convergence indicator that forces high uncertainty $phi >> 1$ on any Gaussian whose pixel footprint contains a color residual exceeding threshold $eta_c$, preventing unconverged Gaussians from becoming key node anchors during graph construction.
-
-The motion locality term $cal(L)_"motion,key"$ enforces four physical constraints over key node neighbourhoods:
-
-$
- cal(L)_"motion" =
- lambda_"iso" cal(L)_"iso"
- + lambda_"rigid" cal(L)_"rigid"
- + lambda_"rot" cal(L)_"rot"
- + lambda_"vel" cal(L)_"vel"
- + lambda_"acc" cal(L)_"acc"
-$
-
-Isometry preserves pairwise distances between graph neighbours over time; rigidity enforces that neighbours undergo consistent rigid-body transformations between consecutive frames; rotation smoothness penalises abrupt changes in relative orientation; velocity and acceleration terms suppress positional and rotational discontinuities.
-
-The non-key node loss introduces an additional Dual Quaternion Blending interpolation target alongside the pretrained anchoring term:
-
-$
- cal(L)_"non-key" =
- sum_t sum_(i in.not V_k)
- norm(bold(p)_(i,t) - bold(p)_(i,t)^circle)_(U^(-1)_(w,i))^2
- + sum_t sum_(i in.not V_k)
- norm(bold(p)_(i,t) - bold(p)^("DQB")_(i,t))_(U^(-1)_(w,i))^2
- + cal(L)_"motion,non-key"
-$
-
-The DQB target $bold(p)^("DQB")_(i,t)$ is obtained by blending the SE(3) transformations of the key node neighbours ${j in cal(E)_i}$ assigned to non-key Gaussian $i$, weighted by inverse Mahalanobis distance:
-
-$
- (bold(p)^("DQB")_(i,t), bold(q)^("DQB")_(i,t)) =
- op("DQB")({(w_(i j), T_(j,t))}_(j in cal(E)_i))
-$
-
-where DQB denotes the dual quaternion blending of Kavan et al. (2007). The target $bold(p)^("DQB")_(i,t)$ constitutes a soft constraint — the actual Gaussian position $bold(p)_(i,t)$ remains a free variable and may deviate from the interpolated prediction when the photometric loss provides a sufficiently strong conflicting signal, preserving the capacity to represent non-rigid deformation.
